<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>DSM Impacts</TITLE></HEAD>
<body background="../hemisph2.gif" BGCOLOR=#999999 link="#004A4A" vlink="#004A4A" TEXT=#000000>

<p>
<img align=left border=0 src="../summitsmall.gif">
<center>
<br><br>
<p><font color="#004A4A"><h2>Website on Hemispheric Experiences in Energy Efficiency
and Renewable Energy</h2></font>
<p><strong><em>Prepared by the U.S. Department of Energy, Office of Energy
Efficiency and Renewable Energy</em></strong>
<p><hr size=3 width=300>
</center>

<br clear=all>
<H2>Impact of DSM Programs</H2>

<P>Assessments of DSM program
impacts are largely non-existent, as most DSM activities in most
countries are in the initial stages of implementation. The <A HREF="http://www.eia.doe.gov/"
>U.S. Energy Information Agency</A> prepares an annual comprehensive
assessment of U.S. utility DSM activities. The <A HREF="http://www.lbl.gov/"
>Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory</A> maintains a U.S. and
International database on the measured performance of energyefficiency
DSM programs. The <A HREF="http://www.epri.com/">Electric Power
Research Institute</A> conducts annual surveys of individual DSM program
descriptions.</P>

<P>In the figure below, the largest U.S. commercial
sector DSM programs are ranked from lowest to highest cost ($/kWh). The
width of each program indicates program size in annual Gwh savings.</P>
<BR>
<B>Total Resource Cost of Commercial Lighting Programs</B>

<HR>
<IMG SRC="dsm.jpeg">

<P><FONT SIZE="2">Source: Eto, J., S. Kito, L. Shown, and R.
Sonnenblick. Where Did the Money Go? The Cost and Performance of the
Largest Commercial Sector DSM Programs. LBL-38201. Berkeley, CA:
Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory. December, 1995.</FONT></P>
